    "body": "### Problem\r\n\r\n(reload/refresh/reset/clear or whatever, i could not find out a more accurate word.)\r\n\r\nwhen writing a plugin rather than a script which can be run `:so/:luafile`, every time i make a change, i have to restart nvim, that's kind of anonying and inefficient;\r\ni remember that plenary.nvim have a similiar [functionality](https://github.com/nvim-lua/plenary.nvim/blob/master/lua/plenary/reload.lua) to do that, but as we now have vim.loader, maybe changes should come to it? but IMO that 'internal' details should not be cared by 3rd plugins.\r\nthere is vim.loader.reset(path), while sometimes vim.loader is just not enabled, and to me `.reset('vim.lsp')` is more intuitive.\r\n\r\n\r\n### Expected behavior\r\n\r\nso i think it's better to provide an api to reload a lua module by nvim itself, like `.reload('foo.bar')`, `.reload('foo.*')`; though i have no idea if `.reload('*')` should be allowed",
